    <!-- What Is Morse Code -->
    <section class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 mb-12">
      <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-accent mb-6">What Is Morse Code?</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Morse code is a telecommunications method that encodes text characters as sequences of dots and dashes, originally developed in the 1830s by Samuel Morse for use with the telegraph system. Each letter, number, and punctuation mark is represented by a unique combination of short signals (dots) and long signals (dashes).
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The most famous morse code signal is SOS (··· −−− ···), which became the international maritime distress signal. Despite being developed nearly 200 years ago, morse code remains relevant today and is still used by amateur radio operators, military personnel, aviation professionals, and maritime communications.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Modern applications include emergency communications when other systems fail, pilot training, military operations, and even assistive technology for people with disabilities. The simple binary nature of morse code makes it incredibly reliable and easy to transmit across various mediums, from light signals to radio waves.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

